## Architecture guidance

- **One contract, everywhere:** every component = typed variants + `cn(base, variants, className)` +
  semantic tokens + built-in a11y. Uniformity is the value.
- **Compose primitives:** Modal uses your focus-trap; Tabs uses custom variants on `data-state`.
- **Headless where it's hard:** wrap a headless library for Tabs/Modal/Menu, style with Tailwind.
- **Govern it:** semver, changelog, deprecation policy — it's a public API now (Module 10).

<Callout type="insight" title="A library's worth is its consistency, not its component count">

It's tempting to measure a library by how many components it has. The real measure is how *predictable*
it is: does knowing one component let you predict the next? Same variant grammar, same override
mechanism, same a11y guarantees, same naming. That predictability is what lets a team adopt it without
reading every source file — they learn the *pattern* once and trust the rest. Ten ruthlessly consistent
components beat fifty inconsistent ones every time. When you build this capstone, obsess over
*uniformity of contract*; it's the difference between a library people love and one they fight. This is
the same restraint Module 10 preached, now expressed as a shippable artifact you can put in a
portfolio.

</Callout>

## Acceptance criteria

- 10+ components sharing one contract (typed variants + cn override + semantic tokens + a11y).
- Barrel export; living gallery rendering all variants in light/dark.
- Role/name-based component tests; CI green; consumable from a second app.
